@stefanv I made it inside the original function because it takes time to load
and parse that file and it's a little bit faster in cython.
Taking into account that usually people will use this framework for detection only on one image, the loading should also be fast.

I've been having some fun trying this out.  My thought is to use `bp::make_constructor` and essentially do runtime type introspection in the pointed to construct function. E.g., for BaseDeviate the construct function and wrapping would look like:

```c++
        static boost::shared_ptr<BaseDeviate> construct(const bp::object &seed) {
            if (seed.ptr() == Py_None) {
                return boost::shared_ptr<BaseDeviate>(new BaseDeviate(0l));
            }
            bp::extract<long> xl(seed);
            if (xl.check()) {
                return boost::shared_ptr<BaseDeviate>(new BaseDeviate(xl()));
            }
            bp::extract<const BaseDeviate&> xbd(seed);
            if (xbd.check()) {
                return boost::shared_ptr<BaseDeviate>(new BaseDeviate(xbd()));
            }
            bp::extract<std::string> xs(seed);
            if (xs.check()) {
                return boost::shared_ptr<BaseDeviate>(new BaseDeviate(xs()));
            }
            throw std::runtime_error("Cannot construct BaseDeviate from given seed.");
        }

        static void wrap() {
            bp::class_<BaseDeviateCallBack>
                pyBaseDeviate("BaseDeviate", "", bp::no_init);
            pyBaseDeviate
                // .def(bp::init<long>(bp::arg("seed")=0))
                // .def(bp::init<const BaseDeviate&>(bp::arg("seed")))
                // .def(bp::init<std::string>(bp::arg("seed")))
                .def("__init__",
                    bp::make_constructor(
                        &construct, bp::default_call_policies(),
                        (bp::arg("seed")=bp::object())
                    ))
                ...
```

This mostly works, except for the virtual override of `_val` in `DistDeviate`, which I'm guessing is the tricky bit you were eluding to above.  I found [this stackoverflow answer](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/19254715/virtual-override-in-boost-python-objects-created-by-static-method-or-factory) which looks relevant, but I thought I'd ask if I'm missing something simpler before tackling that.

