@khalibartan This method was implemented using `defaultdict` only ,so i didn't  thought of changing it. Now, after doing some experiments, i think a normal dict would also suffice this implementation.
Its because, `defaultdict` is similar to the usual dictionary (dict) container, but it has one difference:  that it is initialized with a function  that takes no arguments and provides the default value for a nonexistent key. Thus , a defaultdict will never raise a `KeyError` if you try to get an item with a key that is not currently in the dictionary unlike usual dict container.
Now ,here in this method we are always appending `variables` and its corresponding `cardinality` into the dict container.We are never retrieving a value using a key(either an existing or non-existing key). So ,if their is no retrieval then a normal dict would itself suffice . Please correct me if i am wrong.

I thought about this a little more, and I can't come up with a time when we would want to pass in an `import_path` here (or in `get_db_backend()`). If we want to specify either one explicitly, we can just import and use it directly. `get_db_backend()` is never called with an argument in the code base, although it supports it. I think supporting an `import_path` here is a YAGNI feature, which means this just simplifies down to:

```py
def get_gas_estimator():
    import_path = os.environ.get(
        'GAS_ESTIMATOR_BACKEND_FUNC',
        'evm.estimators.gas.binary_search_intrinsic_tolerance',
    )
    return import_string(import_path)
```

I'm not sure there's much left there to generalize.

It sounds like we might get bug reports for this later, if I understood correctly:

Given two categories: `topic1 -> thing` and `topic2 -> thing`;
Before, `/catalogue/topic/thing` would give the topic -> thing category;
Now it gives whichever of the two categories happens to be sorted first.

Are you sure an explicit cast is necessary here? As far as I know, compilers don't issue warnings for compile-time constants which are guaranteed to fit into the destination type:

```c++
#include <cstddef>

void foo(int) {}

int main() {
    foo(sizeof(float)); // clean (no warnings)
    size_t s = 4;
    foo(s);             // <-- conversion warning here
}
```

GCC, clang and MSVC for example: https://godbolt.org/g/zgibas

This might help avoid some of the casts on the user side.
